Prosper Loan Data Exploration¶

Ghada Bin Muhareb¶

Investigation Overview¶

I'm interested in invetigating the Borrower Annual Percentage Rate (APR) and take a closer look to explore which variables can correlat and affect the Borrower (APR) through visualizations.

Dataset Overview¶

This dataset contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others. Since the dataset includes 81 variables it is difficult to invistigate all of them, so only few of them will be explored.

The distribution of Borrower APR¶

Borrower APR distribution looks multimodal and take a wide range. There is a small peak around 0.1, at 0.2 there is a larger peak, at 0.3 we also have a small peak. Looking at the point between 0.35 and 0.36 we will find a very sharp peak. There are only few loans with APR greater than 0.4.

Most of the borrowers have a rating of C which is in the middle, and we can say most of them fall within the range D-A.

The distribution of the Employment Status¶

Obviously, Most of the borrowers are employed and most of those who are employed are full-time. Part-time, Retired and Not employed are the lowest groups.

The distribution of the Estimated Return of each loan¶

The Estimated Return looks normally distributed, the highest Estimated Return is centered at 0.08 and there is very few loans with Estimated Return less than zero.

Loan Original Amount Vs. Borrower APR¶

There is a negative relationship between the Loan Original Amount and the Borrower APR, as the original amount of the loan was high the Borrower annual percentage rate (APR) will be low.

In [29]:
plt.figure(figsize=[10,6])
sb.regplot(data=loans, x='LoanOriginalAmount', y='BorrowerAPR', x_jitter=0.9, scatter_kws={'alpha':0.01});
plt.title('Loan Original Amount Vs. Borrower APR');
plt.xlabel('Loan Original Amount($)');
plt.ylabel('Borrower APR');

Prosper Rating Vs. Borrower (APR) considering Employment Status¶

There is a strong negative relationship between Prosper Rating and Borrower (APR), The higher ratings of the borrower lead to lower Annual Percentage rate (APR). Employed and self-employed are the largest groups in the ratings E,D and C.

Income Range Vs. Prosper Rating¶

Most of the borrower ratings are located within the income range 25,000-49,999 to 50,000-74,999, some of them are greater than 74,999 and only very few of them are located in the income range 1-24,999.

The interaction between loan terms and ratings for the Loan Original Amount¶

There is an obvious interaction between loan terms and ratings. As much as the Prosper ratings getting higher or better, the loan original amount of all three loan terms getting increased, since the loan original amount increased the term of loans also increases.

In [22]:
plt.figure(figsize=[10,6])
sb.pointplot(data = loans, x = 'ProsperRating', y = 'LoanOriginalAmount', hue = 'Term',
           palette = 'Purples', order=['N/A', 'HR', 'E', 'D', 'C', 'B', 'A', 'AA']);

plt.title('The interaction between loan terms and ratings for the Loan Original Amount');
plt.xlabel('Prosper Rating');
plt.ylabel('Loan Original Amount($)');

Comparing Estimated Return with Borrower APR for each Prosper Rating¶

The highest ratings of the borrower is the lowest Annual Percentage Rate (APR) with almost the same estimatd return, except the lowest rating (HR) which has lower estimatd return and higher Annual Percentage Rate (APR). The highest Estimated Return acheived almost in the Ratings (E,D and C).

                 palette = 'colorblind');

g.add_legend();

g.fig.suptitle('Comparing Estimated Return with Borrower APR for each Prosper Rating', fontsize=13);

Key Insights¶

  • As much as the borrowers choose a higher loan original amount this will contribute to decrease the Anuual Percentage Reate (APR).
  • Higher prosper ratings of borrowers allow for larger loan original amount and longer term.
  • Lower prosper ratings lead to higher Annual Percentage Rate (APR).
  • The highest Estimated Return acheived almost in the Ratings (E,D and C).
